INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9b086303-a26c-4087-b29a-8615b00027bc',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Node.js Standard Library — What's Built In vs What Needs npm$escape$,
  $escape$Node.js ships with a surprisingly capable standard library, but developers routinely reach for npm when they don't need to — and miss it when they do.

Built-in and battle-ready: `node:fs/promises` for async file I/O, `node:crypto` for hashing/HMAC/AES (no need for `bcryptjs` for SHA-256), `node:stream` with `pipeline()` for backpressure-safe streaming, `node:worker_threads` for CPU-bound work, `node:test` (added in v18) as a Jest-lite replacement, `node:sqlite` (v22.5+) for embedded SQL, and `node:http`/`node:https` for raw servers.

Still worth npm: date manipulation (`date-fns`), schema validation (`zod`), HTTP clients with retries and interceptors (`axios`, `got`), structured logging (`pino`), and bcrypt password hashing (`bcryptjs` — Node's `crypto` won't do adaptive cost).

The inflection point: if a built-in covers your use case without ceremony, use it — fewer supply-chain attack surfaces, zero install overhead, and no version drift. Always import with the `node:` prefix to make stdlib intent explicit and avoid shadowing by accidental npm packages.$escape$,
  $escape$import { randomBytes, createHmac } from 'node:crypto';
import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';
import { createReadStream, createWriteStream } from 'node:fs';
import { gzip } from 'node:zlib';

// HMAC-SHA256 — no npm needed
const sig = createHmac('sha256', process.env.SECRET)
  .update('payload')
  .digest('hex');

// Backpressure-safe gzip — no 'archiver' needed
await pipeline(
  createReadStream('input.log'),
  gzip(),
  createWriteStream('input.log.gz')
);$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
